$interpreted: Himawari: With her here, Juan-yun will never choose me!
Himawari: Dammit...!!
Himawari: Juan-yun, wait for me!
Soohyeon: ......
Toyokuni: ......
Soohyeon: ...We’ve done something... unforgivable.
Toyokuni: I understand how you feel, but we had no choice.

Soohyeon: Really...?
Did we really have no other choice?

Toyokuni: Anyway, there’s no point thinking about it now.
Let’s just go inside.
Soohyeon: ...Tindoiimu... I’m sorry...
Pang: (...Soohyeon is right. Was there really no other way we could help Tindoiimu?)
Pang: (Wait a second, that human diplomat said something before...)
Pang: That’s right! It’s the only way!
Pang: (This is a long shot, but I might get lucky. Maybe he felt safe and came back...)
Pang: —Yao!?
Pang: What on Vendacti are you doing here? Are you looking for the artisan, as well?
Yao: ...As well? What business do you have with the artisan?
Pang: Ah... I’m here to ask for his help.
Pang: Do you know each other? Then, maybe I could ask you—
Yao: I wouldn’t say I know him. I just ordered something from him. He told me to come back this afternoon to pick it up.
Pang: What did you order?
Yao: Just some... things. Nothing to do with you.
Pang: I guess he didn’t return...
Yao: You guess? Do you know something I don’t?
Pang: That human diplomat came looking for him a little while ago. The artisan saw him and ran... now I think he’s too scared to come back.
Pang: I came by to see if he had returned, but... no luck.
Yao: ...Damn.
Pang: Yao!?
Pang: Those soldiers from the Kingdom of the Sun already went through here. They didn't find anything of importance...
Yao: Hmph. That’s because they didn’t know what to look for.
Pang: Hold on, where are we going?
Yao: ...We’re going to find this comb’s owner.
Pang: ...What’s so special about this comb? Looks pretty ordinary to me.
Yao: You'd think so.
Yao: It’s called a grass comb, the guesthouse girls here make them themselves. They carry a special meaning... outsiders wouldn’t know.
Pang: And why does a Tiger Tribe prince know about local customs?
Yao: Hmph... Prince, huh? That was a long time ago... seems like another life now.
Pang: ...Yao...
Yao: People like us, on the bottom rungs of society, can sniff each other out. Exiled princes, working girls... it doesn’t matter.
Yao: I’ve been a vagabond for four years now, and Hot Spring Street gets all sorts. People don’t ask questions. Someone like me can blend in here.
Yao: —Beyata.
Beyata: What a coincidence, I was just thinking about you, Yao~ I heard you were out on the road. When did you come back?
Yao: ...Felt like I should come back, so I did.
Yao: I’ve got a question for you. Does this comb belong to any of the girls here?
Beyata: Ah... what do you mean, Yao?
Yao: These combs aren't something you can just buy on the street.
Yao: Girls only give them to the men they’re interested in.
Yao: Don't play dumb with me, Beyata.
Yao: You know I won't fall for it.
Beyata: ......
Beyata: ...It’s not that I don’t want to help you, but...
Beyata: You know what these grass combs represent. A girl's heart is her own secret, Yao.
Beyata: I don’t want to say anything that could get a girl’s heart broken.
Guest: Hmph!
Pang: Yao, what's wrong...
Yao: Heartbroken!? And what if she's heartless? Could you still break her heart then!?
Yao: Maybe you should get her heart broken! That's the best way to cope in this cold, dark world!
Rude Guest: Relax, nutcase, or go back to the loony bin!
Scared Guest: Agh, he's frightening!
Beyata: Yao, stop it! You're scaring me!
Beyata: You’re ruining everything... what a mess...
Beyata: I don’t understand, you were always so good to us! Why would you get so angry all of a sudden!?
Pang: Stop this, Yao, you’ve made the lady cry—
Beyata: I understand... You want to play with me, don’t you, Yao?
Beyata: If it would make you feel better, then I'll gladly be your bluebird~
Yao: Try me!
Confused Girl: Bluebird? What’s going on?
Curious Girl: Ah, isn't that Yao!?
Drunk Guest: Beyata... *hic*... someone else tearin’ their heart out for you now? *hic*
Yao: All you have to do is answer me, and I’ll leave. Otherwise I’ll just keep kicking up more of a fuss.
Beyata: Ugh... Fine, just come with me.
Beyata: ...Let me see that comb again.
Beyata: You want to know who this belongs to, huh...
Yao: Don’t worry, I won’t bring any harm to her.

Beyata: Well... alright, then. 
Just wait here.
